Thus for low ksp, the energy of the SPs will tend to assume the value of the thickest, bottom most layer, and as ksp increases, changes in the SP energy will occur as the SP assumes the value appropriate for the layer within which its fields are increasingly confined. Figures 7, 8, 9, and 10 illustrate this concept for a simulated 3-layer system (with two additional semi-infinite layers being the superstrate and substrate of ɛ = 4). The structure has 3 layers of different doping, layers 2, 3, and 4. Layer 2 has the following properties: n2 = 1.9 × 1015 cm−3 and t2 = 15 nm; Layer 3 n3 = 2.6 × 1015 cm−3 and t3 = 20 nm; Layer 4 n4 = 4.3 × 1015 cm−3 and t4 = 1 µm. All layers have μe=1.5×105cm2/V s\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
